=================
| Encapsulation |
=================
👉 Encapsulation is the process of binding data (variables) and methods (functions) into a single unit (class) 
    and restricting direct access to the data.

Encapsulation
↓
Enclose
↓
closed inside a box

Python usese naming conventions and name mangling

1️⃣ Public Members (Default access.) access every where

    class Student:
        def __init__(self):
            self.name = "Mridul"
    s1 = Student()
    print(s1.name)

O/P : Mridul

2️⃣ Protected Members (strart using single underscore _ )

    class Student:
        def __init__(self):
            self._age = 21
    s1 = Student()
    print(s1._age)

O/P : 21

👉 Python does not strictly enforce encapsulation or access control like languages such as Java or C++ do. Instead, 
    Python relies entirely on naming conventions and developer discipline. 

3️⃣ Private Members  (Double underscore (__) )

    class Student:
        def __init__(self):
            self.__salary = 50000
    s1 = Student()
    print(s1.__salary)

O/P : AttributeError

👉 Name Mangling 
    Actually Python changed variable name
    
self.__salary -> _Student__salary

-----------------
| Getter Method |
-----------------
👉 This method use for read a private data

class Student:
    def __init__(self):
        self.__salary = 50000

    def get_salary(self):
        return self.__salary

s1 = Student()
print(s1.get_salary())

O/P : 50000

-----------------
| Setter Method |
-----------------
👉 This method use for updating private data

class Student:
    def __init__(self):
        self.__salary = 50000

    def set_salary(self, salary):
        if salary > 0:
            self.__salary = salary

s1 = Student()
s1.set_salary(70000)
print(s1.get_salary())

O/P : 70000

